# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: becherovka
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:becherovka/100-pipers] 100 Pipers is bottled and marketed in India.
[src:becherovka/100-pipers] 100 Pipers is a blend of between 25 and 30 source whiskies that came from Scotland.
[src:becherovka/100-pipers] Much of it comes from the Allt a'Bhainne distillery, which is also owned by Pernod Ricard and does not have its own bottling facilities.
[src:becherovka/100-pipers] In addition to India, it is also distributed in Thailand, other Asian countries and South America.
[src:becherovka/100-pipers] 2 standard whisky in Asia", and the "No.
[src:becherovka/100-pipers] The brand owes its name and Celtic imagery to the Scottish tradition of bagpipers leading soldiers into battle.
[src:becherovka/100-pipers] The "100 Pipers" name in particular comes from the ballad of "The Hundred Pipers", which tells of the heroic Bonnie Prince Charlie's (1720–1788) 1745 Jacobite uprising led by a troop of 100 bagpipers.
[src:becherovka/100-pipers] The brand is marketed with the promotional slogan *True Legend*.
[src:becherovka/100-pipers] The website RankingtheBrands.com rated the brand value of 100 Pipers 75th in 2011 and 81st in 2014 among 10,000 spirit brands worldwide.
[src:becherovka/100-pipers] 100 Pipers sponsors an annual "India Music Week" festival.
[src:becherovka/100-pipers] 100 Pipers is one of the best-selling whiskies in Thailand.
[src:becherovka/100-pipers] A limited-edition "Night Bottle" for 100 Pipers was released in Thailand in 2015 with a fashion show-themed silicone wrap accompanying the bottle design.
[src:becherovka/100-pipers] 100 Pipers received a Gold Medal at "The Asian Spirits Masters 2014".
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] James Fleming (1830–1895) was born and baptised on the first day of June at Inveravon, the only son of a tenant farmer at Tomfarclas on the Ballindalloch estate.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] James helped his father on the farm until manhood and then sought a wider and more financially rewarding direction for his future, first as a commission agent and dealer in the grain trade.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] In the mid-1860s, he acquired a lease of the Dailuaine distillery at nearby Carron and held it for ten years, making connections in the spirit markets.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] By the 1871 Census, James had moved to Aberlour, and in 1874 established and developed a new branch agency for the North of Scotland Bank.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] He became a prominent and respected member of the local community; as an elder of the parish church and in several public positions: chairman of the School Board, county councillor, and town Provost.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] In 1879, Fleming secured a feu from the Earl of Fife on the land where he planned to build the Aberlour distillery and, upon its completion, produced whisky there from December 1880.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] He sold the business to his acting agents, Robert Thorne & Sons in 1892.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] James Fleming died aged 65, leaving a significant and tangible legacy.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] He built Aberlour's first public meeting place, The Fleming Hall in 1889.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] This was followed in 1900 by the Fleming Cottage Hospital providing isolation accommodation to limit the spread of infectious diseases.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] In James Thomson's 1902 book *Recollections of a Speyside Parish*, the author wrote: "The hospital that has been built and endowed by his [Fleming's] liberality will always remain a memorial to his Christian philanthropy.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] I can well remember more than one epidemic that devastated many a home in the village.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] After delays in its approval by an obstinate landowner, the Victoria Bridge, Aberlour – often referred to as the Penny Bridge locally – was completed and opened without ceremony in 1902.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] James Fleming is buried in the town's cemetery almost opposite the distillery site.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] Robert Thorne & Sons Ltd. sold the Aberlour distillery in 1920 to a brewing family, W.H.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] Holt & Sons, based near Manchester, England.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] Campbell & Sons Ltd and the distillery was later re-equppied with four stills in 1973.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] In 1975, Pernod Ricard acquired Campbell Distilleries, and they joined with Chivas Brothers in 2001 forming a portfolio of 14 single malt distilleries and one grain distillery in Scotland, and two gin distilleries in England.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] In 2002, a new modernised visitor centre was opened for public visits and tours.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] In 2014, over 3.5 million bottles of Aberlour were sold.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] The whisky comes in a variety of ages, including a 10, 12, 15, 16, 18 and a rare 30-year-old 1970 vintage malt, as well as a cask strength release, A'bunadh, with no age statement.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] Most of the variants are aged in American ex-bourbon casks, a standard for many single malts.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] Aberlour also releases a range of malts that, after aging in bourbon casks, are finished in casks previously used to mature varieties of fortified wines or sherries, a method applied to appeal particularly to the French market.
[src:becherovka/aberlour-distillery] Since 1986, Aberlour Single Malt Scotch Whisky has won 58 Gold awards and 8 Trophies in the Tasting categories of two leading industry competitions, the International Wine and Spirits Competition (IWSC) and International Spirits Challenge (ISC).
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:becherovka/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:becherovka/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:becherovka/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Absolut was established in 1879 by Lars Olsson Smith.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Smith challenged the city of Stockholm's liquor marketing monopoly with his vodka.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] It was sold outside the city border at a lower price than the monopoly's product.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Smith offered free boat rides to the distillery and *Rent Brännvin* ("Pure Vodka") was highly successful.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In 1917, the Swedish government monopolized the country's alcohol industry.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Vodka was then sold nationwide under the name *Absolut Rent Brännvin*.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In 1979, the old name Absolut was picked up when the upper-price range Absolut Vodka was introduced.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] *Renat* is the name of another vodka product sold by Pernod Ricard Sweden AB.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Absolut Vodka was introduced to the global market in 1979.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] As of 2018 Absolut sells over 100 million litres (26,000,000 US gal) of vodka annually.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] The vodka is made from winter wheat and is produced only in Åhus.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Lars Olsson Smith was born in 1836 in Kiaby and died in 1913 in Karlskrona, Sweden.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Smith was an entrepreneur, parliamentarian and founder of *Absolut Rent Brännvin* ("Absolutely pure spirit").
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] It was the inspiration for Absolut Vodka.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Smith launched a method that removes contaminants such as glut in the spirits.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Smith came from a peasant family in Blekinge and quickly made a career in the retail trade as a 6-year-old.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] He later moved to Stockholm and started manufacturing and selling vodka at his factory at Reimersholme.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In the early 1980s in New York, Absolut Vodka was popular among the creative community.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Absolut's first advertising campaign was created by TBWA for the brand's U.S.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] The brand has a long-running advertising campaign created by TBWA.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] The first of these ads, typical of the rest, was introduced in 1981 and featured a picture of the bottle with a halo over the cap above the slogan "Absolut Perfection".
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Absolut's first advertising campaign ran for more than twenty-five years from its launch in 1980.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] The campaign has encompassed many different kinds of ads, such as art, fashion, cities, spectaculars, Hollywood, etc.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Their advertising has won hundreds of awards, including charter membership in the American Marketing Association's Marketing Hall of Fame.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Absolut was inducted into the Hall in 1992 along with just two other brands: Coca-Cola and Nike.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Also in 1992, Freedom Rings were featured in the first gay-specific Absolut Vodka ad, entitled *Absolut Spada*.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In 1983, Carillon's president and CEO Michel Roux approached the artist Andy Warhol, whom he paid $65,000 to create an advertisement for Absolut as part of the brand's iconic Absolut Art Initiative.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In the 1990s, Absolut Vodka began granting the *Artist of the Year* title to select visual artists, a distinction that came with a guaranteed global advertising placement.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] These campaigns blurred the boundaries between marketing and contemporary art, making the title a coveted marker of prestige in the creative world.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] By partnering with high-profile names like David LaChapelle, Robert Rauschenberg, Keith Haring, and Jean-Michel Basquiat, Absolut spotlighted both the brand and the featured artists on an international stage, solidifying the brand's connection to the world of modern art.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Over the years, Carillon commissioned the work of well-known painters, graphic designers, fashion designers, as well as many up-and-coming artists.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] During the 2017 Corporate Art Awards Ceremony hosted by the President of the Italian Republic Sergio Mattarella at the Quirinal Palace, Absolut received by pptArt a special award "for their long-running collaboration with 550 artists on 850 projects to shape their corporate image and brand".
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] The talents included such names as Damien Hirst, Rosemarie Trockel, Helmut Newton, Javier Mariscal, Maurizio Cattelan, Louise Bourgeois, Alain Despert, Ron English, Giancarlo Impiglia, and many, many more.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In 1996 Richard Lewis the Chiat/Day executive who ran the Absolut art campaign for the advertising firm published "Absolut Book: The Absolut Vodka Advertising Story" (Journey Editions).
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In 2005, Absolut invited American singer Lenny Kravitz to participate in its promotional campaign.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] The song "Breathe" was recorded and released.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] The song was remixed many times by various DJs.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In 2007, Absolut introduced its new global campaign, "In An Absolut World", created by TBWA/Chiat/Day.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In 2008, an advertisement placed in Mexican publications and on Mexican billboards featured a map of the U.S. and Mexico with the boundaries between the two as they were prior to the 1836 Texas Revolution and the Mexican–American War.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Media outlets reported on some American consumers' reactions at the advert's perceived insensitivity to immigration issues.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Absolut responded that the adverts were purely whimsical, with no political or nationalist agenda, but its critics were adamant.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Absolut later issued a public apology and withdrew the advert.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In 2009, Absolut debuted a campaign with renowned fashion photographer Ellen Von Unwerth and actresses Kate Beckinsale and Zooey Deschanel to celebrate different Absolut drinks.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In the same year, the brand launched the Absolut Art Awards to commemorate 30 years of collaboration with the world of modern art.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In 2010 Absolut collaborated with Spike Jonze to create a short film entitled *I’m here*.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] The short film was screened at festivals such as Sundance Film Festival and Berlin Film Festival.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In 2012, Absolut partnered with Swedish House Mafia to create an original track and music video to promote Absolut Greyhound cocktail.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] "Greyhound"–which is the title of the drink, the video, and the actual music track–is a video created by TBWA\Chiat\Day, where three groups of racing enthusiasts converge on the Bonneville Salt Flats to watch robotic greyhounds speed across the plains, holding pink Absolut Greyhounds in their hands.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In 2013, Absolut launched the Global 'Transform Today' Campaign by the creative agency, Sid Lee.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Sid Lee recruited four international emerging artists to inspire younger generations.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] French artist, director and musician Woodkid, American digital media artist Aaron Koblin, fashion designer Yiqing Yin and Brazilian graphic novel artists Rafael Grampa is featured.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] As part of this platform, Absolut launched the Absolut Creative Competition in 2018 which was an art competition.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] In May 2019 Absolut announced the global winner that was selected by global juries such as Mickalene Thomas, Aaron Cezar and Bose Krishnamachari.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] Sarah Saroufim from Lebanon was declared the winner from 7,500 entrants with her design.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] After pausing its production in Russia due to the Russian invasion of Ukraine in February 2022, Pernod Ricard resumed the export of Absolut Vodka in April 2023, leading to widespread criticism in Sweden.
[src:becherovka/absolut-vodka] As a result, Pernod Ricard decided to once again stop its operations in Russia.
[src:becherovka/abv] France, alcohol by volume is often referred to as **degrees Gay-Lussac** (after the French chemist Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac), although there is a slight difference since the Gay-Lussac convention uses the International Standard Atmosphere value for temperature, 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:becherovka/abv] Mixing two solutions of alcohol of different strengths usually causes a change in volume.
[src:becherovka/abv] Mixing pure water with a solution less than 24% by mass causes a slight increase in total volume, whereas the mixing of two solutions above 24% causes a decrease in volume.
[src:becherovka/abv] The phenomenon of volume changes due to mixing dissimilar solutions is called "partial molar volume".
[src:becherovka/abv] Water and ethanol are both polar solvents.
[src:becherovka/abv] When water is added to ethanol, the smaller water molecules are attracted to the ethanol's hydroxyl group, and each molecule alters the polarity field of the other.
[src:becherovka/abv] The attraction allows closer spacing between molecules than is usually found in non-polar mixtures.
[src:becherovka/abv] Thus, alc/vol is not the same as volume fraction expressed as a percentage.
[src:becherovka/abv] Volume fraction, which is widely used in chemistry (commonly denoted as v/v), is defined as the volume of a particular component divided by the sum of all components in the mixture when they are measured separately.
[src:becherovka/abv] For example, to make 100 mL of 50% alc/vol ethanol solution, water would be added to 50 mL of ethanol to make up exactly 100 mL.
[src:becherovka/abv] Whereas to make a 50% v/v ethanol solution, 50 mL of ethanol and 50 mL of water could be mixed but the resulting volume of solution will measure less than 100 mL due to the change of volume on mixing, and will contain a higher concentration of ethanol.
[src:becherovka/abv] The difference is not large, with the maximum difference being less than 2.5%, and less than 0.5% difference for concentrations under 20%.
[src:becherovka/abv] Some drinks have requirements of alcoholic content in order to be certified as a certain alcohol brand or label.
[src:becherovka/abv] For example, in the United Kingdom, the United States, Canada and European Union whisky is legally required to be no less than 40% ABV bottled.
[src:becherovka/abv] Low-alcohol beers (<0.5) are considered in some countries such as Iran as permitted (halal) despite alcohol being banned.
[src:becherovka/abv] However, the level of alcohol-free beers is typically the lowest commercially sold 0.05.
[src:becherovka/abv] It is near impossible for a healthy person to become intoxicated drinking low-alcohol drinks.
[src:becherovka/abv] The low concentration severely limits the rate of intake, which is easily dispatched by human metabolism.
[src:becherovka/abv] Quickly drinking 1.5 L of 0.4% alc/vol beer in an hour resulted in a maximum of 0.0056% BAC in a study of German volunteers.
[src:becherovka/abv] Healthy human kidneys can only excrete 0.8–1.0 L of water per hour, making water intoxication likely to set in before any alcoholic intoxication.
[src:becherovka/abv] The process of ethanol fermentation will slow down and eventually come to a halt as the alcohol produced becomes too concentrated for the yeast to tolerate, defining an upper limit of alc/vol for non-distilled alcoholic drinks.
[src:becherovka/abv] The typical tolerance for beer yeasts is at 8–12%, while wine yeasts typically range from 14–18%, with speciality ones reaching 20% alc/vol.
[src:becherovka/abv] Any higher would require distillation, producing liquor.
[src:becherovka/abv] Details about typical amounts of alcohol contained in various beverages can be found in the articles about them.
[src:becherovka/abv] During the production of wine and beer, yeast is added to a sugary solution.
[src:becherovka/abv] During fermentation, the yeasts consume the sugars and produce alcohol.
[src:becherovka/abv] The density of sugar in water is greater than the density of alcohol in water.
[src:becherovka/abv] A hydrometer is used to measure the change in specific gravity (SG) of the solution before and after fermentation.
[src:becherovka/abv] The volume of alcohol in the solution can then be estimated.
[src:becherovka/abv] There are a number of empirical formulae which brewers and winemakers use to estimate the alcohol content of the liquor made.
[src:becherovka/abv] Specific gravity is the density of a liquid relative to that of water, i.e., if the density of the liquid is 1.05 times that of water, it has a specific gravity of 1.05.
[src:becherovka/abv] In UK brewing usage, it is customary to regard the reference value for water to be 1000, so the specific gravity of the same example beer would be quoted as 1050.
[src:becherovka/abv] The formulas here assume that the former definition is used for specific gravity.
[src:becherovka/abv] During ethanol fermentation the yeast converts one mole of sugar into two moles of alcohol.
[src:becherovka/abv] where 46.069 is the molar mass of ethanol and 180.156 is the molar mass of glucose and fructose.
[src:becherovka/abv] SG can be measured using an hydrometer and Brix can be calculated from SG.
[src:becherovka/abv] SG drop is how much the SG decreased during fermentation (at 20 degree C).
[src:becherovka/abv] The factor 135 is most accurate in the center of the SG drop range of 0.000 to 0.179.
[src:becherovka/abv] Advanced formula derived from Carl Balling empirical formulas.
[src:becherovka/abv] The formula compensates for changes in SG with changes in alcohol concentration and for the fact that not all sugar is converted into alcohol.
[src:becherovka/abv] where SG final is the specific gravity when fermentation ends, Plato start is the sugar by weight when fermentation begins, Plato final is the sugar by weight when fermentation ends.
[src:becherovka/abv] Brix can be used instead of Plato as they are nearly identical.
[src:becherovka/abv] Another way of specifying the amount of alcohol content is alcohol *proof*, which in the United States is twice the alcohol-by-volume (alc/vol) number.
[src:becherovka/abv] This may lead to confusion over similar products bought in varying regions that have different names on country-specific labels.
[src:becherovka/abv] For example, Stroh rum that is 80% ABV is advertised and labeled as *Stroh 80* when sold in Europe, but is named *Stroh 160* when sold in the United States.
[src:becherovka/abv] In the United Kingdom, proof is 1.75 times the number (expressed as a percentage).
[src:becherovka/abv] For example, 40% alc/vol is 80 proof in the US and 70 proof in the UK.
[src:becherovka/abv] However, since 1980, alcohol proof in the UK has been replaced by alc/vol as a measure of alcohol content, avoiding confusion between the UK and US proof standards.
[src:becherovka/abv] In the United States, Arkansas, Kansas, Mississippi, South Carolina, and Tennessee regulate and tax alcoholic beverages according to **alcohol by weight** (**ABW**), expressed as a percentage of total mass.
[src:becherovka/abv] The alc/vol value of a beverage is always higher than the ABW.
[src:becherovka/abv] Because ABW measures the proportion of the drink's mass which is alcohol, while alc/vol is the proportion of the drink's volume which is alcohol, the two values are in the same proportion as the drink's density is with the density of alcohol.
[src:becherovka/abv] At relatively low alc/vol, the alcohol percentage by weight is about 4/5 of the alc/vol (e.g., 3.2% ABW is about 4% alc/vol).
[src:becherovka/abv] However, because of the miscibility of alcohol and water, the conversion factor is not constant but rather depends upon the concentration of alcohol.
[src:becherovka/acerum] In the 1970s, distillers began to produce alcohol from maple syrup.
[src:becherovka/acerum] Although some distilled alcohol tests were then carried out in university laboratories, it was not until the 1990s that certain maple syrup producers began to produce a wine based on this sweet resource, which was initially called Acer.
[src:becherovka/acerum] One of the first producers of Acerum was The Domaine Acer, based in Témiscouata, Quebec.
[src:becherovka/acerum] When Vallier Robert took the reins of his family maple business in 1990, he quickly saw the potential to make alcohol.
[src:becherovka/acerum] In 1996, the maple farmer was granted the first licence to produce artisanal maple-based alcoholic beverages.
[src:becherovka/acerum] He began creating several varieties of maple sap wine, including dry, sparkling and dessert wines.
[src:becherovka/acerum] During the same period, some distilleries began to market maple eau-de-vie, but it was not until December 2017 that the name Acerum appeared for the first time for a maple eau-de-vie.
[src:becherovka/acerum] As defined by the specifications of the UDSÉ, Acerum must be entirely manufactured in the province of Quebec, in Canada, with maple syrup, maple concentrate, or maple sap from Quebec maples.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] Two theories have been put out on the origins of "advocaat".
[src:becherovka/advocaat] According to several makers, such as Verpoorten and Bols, and the *Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets*, its origins can be traced back to "abacate", an alcoholic beverage of the indigenous people in Brazil, which was made with avocado.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] Dutch colonials of northern Brazil introduced this beverage to Europe as "advocat/advocaat".
[src:becherovka/advocaat] As avocados could not grow in northern Europe, they were replaced with egg yolk, thought to have a similar taste and consistency, and the name derived from the avocado stuck, although the drink no longer contains any.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] Cooymans started a distillery in downtown 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] There he developed the egg drink "advocaat".
[src:becherovka/advocaat] In 1876, the Antwerp distiller Eugen Verpoorten established a distillery in Heinsberg near Aachen, Germany, which made an egg liqueur (*Eierlikör* in German) using eggs, sugar, distilled alcohol, and other ingredients.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] Jars and wide mouth bottles of thick advocaat are sold mainly in the Netherlands and Belgium, though may be available in Germany, Austria, and South Africa.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] Further exports are of a more liquid version.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] In particular the original thick variety, i.e., without albumen, is used as a waffle, pancake or poffertjes topping, as an ingredient in ice cream, custards, pastries and similar desserts, or as an apéritif or digestif.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] The latter, possibly topped with whipped cream and then occasionally sprinkled with a touch of cocoa powder, is served in a very tiny bowl or small glass from which it is eaten by use of a teaspoon.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] In Belgian restaurants and taverns, it may be a complementary accompaniment to a coffee.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] In the export variety both parts of the eggs are used.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] A popular cocktail using advocaat is the Snowball: a mixture of advocaat, sparkling lemonade and sometimes (although this is not required) lime juice that is often consumed at Christmas time.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] Another is the Fluffy duck, made with rum.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] Another advocaat-based beverage is the Bombardino, a drink commonly found in Italian ski resorts, particularly the Italian Alps, made by mixing advocaat, brandy, and whipped cream.
[src:becherovka/advocaat] The Polish equivalent, *ajerkoniak* (German: *eier* 'eggs' and French: *cognac*), is based on vodka instead of brandy, despite what the name may suggest.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] Becherovka is often described as having a gingery or cinnamon flavor.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] Its alcohol content is 38% ABV (76 proof), and it is usually served chilled.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] The inventor of Becher Bitter was Josef Vitus Becher (1769–1840) from the city then known as Carlsbad, later spelled Karlsbad.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] Apart from trading in spices and colonial goods in his shop, "Haus der drei Lerchen / Dům U Tří skřivanů" ("House of the Three Woodlarks"), he also produced alcoholic beverages.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] In 1794, he rented a still-house and began to experiment with spirits.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] In 1805 Prince Maxmillian Friedrich von Plettenberg arrived in Carlsbad for medical treatment, accompanied by his personal physician, Christian Frobrig from England.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] Frobrig discussed with Josef Becher the strength of herbs and the recipe for a new liqueur.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] Becher tested this recipe for two years, after which he began selling this new "English Bitter" liqueur, which was intended for the treatment of diseases of the stomach.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] Josef married twice (his first wife died of pneumonia) and had a total of 16 children, though only five daughters and two sons outlived him.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] Josef's son Johann (Jan) Nepomuk Becher took over the still-house in 1838.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] He built a new factory and is considered as the founder of the company.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] His product was sold under the name of "Becher Carlsbad Bitter Liqueur" from about the 1830s on.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] During the First World War, his Karlsbader Becherbitter was sold in Bohemia, Austria, Germany, Poland, Spain, Italy, Turkey and Egypt.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] After the end of Prohibition in the United States, the Becherbitter went on sale in that country and four years later also in England.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] After the Second World War, Karlsbader Becherbitter became known as Becherovka following the dispossession and forceful expulsion of the German population of Karlovy Vary by the Czech state (see Beneš decrees).
[src:becherovka/becherovka] Becherovka became one of Czechoslovakia's most popular export items.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] From 1998 to 2003, a Slovak version also was sold.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] This was manufactured by Zdeněk Hoffmann domestically (Domažlice) and sold in Slovak shops.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] Hoffmann claimed that Alfred Becher had given his grandfather the recipe in 1939 with the right to manufacture the product, since he had been worried that the secret of his recipe might not survive the war.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] However, Hoffmann was unable to prove this in court, and in 2008 he was sentenced by the district court to a year and a half in jail.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] The Czech producer says that only two people know the full details of the production process and are allowed to enter the *Drogikamr* room – where, once a week, they mix the herbs and spices used in the drink.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] Some of the herbs are imported from abroad, and some grow around Karlovy Vary.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] Some serve Becherovka with tonic water, making a drink called a *beton* (Becherovka and tonic), which means "concrete" in Czech and many other languages.
[src:becherovka/becherovka] This cocktail was originally created for Expo 67 in Montreal as a refreshment to be served in the Czech Pavilion.
